{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:58:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:58:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1017"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1017"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.01,0.1,0.78,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111843"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1017"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93913"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"207"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45406"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111843"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with chest pain and undergoes emergency percutaneous coronary intervention for an anterior myocardial infarction. He is making a good post-operative recovery, but on day three becomes confused and voluble. He has been receiving 1g paracetamol QID for pre-existing osteoarthritis of his knees. His pre-op notes state that he is a non-smoker and drinks \u0027a few beers on the weekend\u0027. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe will not stay still on the bed for a physical examination, and appears sweaty and agitated. On closer inspection, he has a visible tremor in both hands. His observation charts show a blood pressure of 130/80 mmHg, pulse 95/min, respiratory rate 16/min, temperature 37.2\u00b0C and oxygen saturations 97% on room air. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atelectasis","Septic shock","Paracetamol toxicity","Alcohol withdrawal","Hyponatraemia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are many possible causes for confusion in the post-operative setting and these patients need a careful assessment. Hopefully there will be documentation in the case records of the patient\u0027s state of health prior to admission, the medications they may have been taking and alcohol consumption. Even without knowing the history, the observation of agitation, volubility, sweating, and hand tremors three days after admission does make \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcohol withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E an important diagnosis to consider. In the given circumstances it is the most plausible diagnosis. It does not have to be a high level of alcohol intake - but regular alcohol intake which is now being denied, as he is in hospital. The patient\u0027s reported \u0027few beers on weekends\u0027 may be an underestimation of his actual consumption. It is important for medical practitioners taking a history to appreciate that many patients will not admit to their level of alcohol consumption - and less likely to a habit of regular and dependent consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlcohol withdrawal is a frequently overlooked diagnosis in hospitalised patients, particularly when there is no documented history of alcohol use. Many individuals do not disclose their alcohol consumption during admission due to stigma, embarrassment, or fear of judgment. Others may genuinely underestimate their intake or not recognise their dependence. The classic presentation of unexplained agitation, tremor, diaphoresis, and autonomic instability emerging 48-72 hours after admission should prompt consideration of withdrawal, even in patients without an established alcohol use history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtelectasis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given that the patient\u0027s vital signs, including oxygen saturations and respiratory rate, are within normal limits. For the same reason, \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptic shock\u003C/strong\u003E is also an unlikely diagnosis. However, it is still very important to think about sepsis, given its significant morbidity and mortality. The Australian Commission on Safety and Quality in Healthcare runs a sepsis awareness campaign for this reason: \u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/about-us/latest-news/our-campaigns/sepsis-campaign\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/about-us/latest-news/our-campaigns/sepsis-campaign\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given that the dose of paracetamol is reasonable for adults over 50kg without renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E, while possible, is unlikely to have arisen so acutely, particularly if the patient was making a good recovery up until now.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alcohol withdrawal symptoms usually develop within several hours to a few days after cessation of alcohol use.","Tremors, agitation, diaphoresis, and tachycardia are classic signs of alcohol withdrawal syndrome.","Patients often underreport alcohol consumption, making withdrawal an important consideration in unexplained post-admission delirium."],"references":["Elliott, Dolores Y. Caring for hospitalized patients with alcohol withdrawal syndrome. Nursing Critical Care. 2019;14(5):18-30. doi: 10.1097/01.CCN.0000578828.37034.c2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1017"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93913"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T14:01:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T14:02:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1017"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111843"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synony